      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Simulating a PRM with LLM Step Scoring"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Without a trained reward model, a capable LLM can act as a step-level evaluator. The key is prompting it to assess a single step given its prior context, producing a score and a short justification:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import anthropic, json, re\nfrom concurrent.futures import ThreadPoolExecutor\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\nSTEP_SCORE_PROMPT = \"\"\"You are a mathematical reasoning evaluator.\nRate the correctness of this single reasoning step on a scale of 0.0 to 1.0.\n\nProblem: {problem}\nSteps so far:\n{prior_steps}\nStep to evaluate:\n{current_step}\n\nConsider:\n- Is this step logically valid given the prior steps?\n- Does it follow the right method?\n- Is the arithmetic or algebra correct?\n\nReply ONLY with a JSON object: {\"score\": <0.0-1.0>, \"reason\": \"<one sentence>\"}\nNo markdown, no extra text.\"\"\"\n\ndef score_step(problem: str, prior_steps: list[str], current_step: str) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Score a single reasoning step given the problem and prior context.\"\"\"\n    raw = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=256,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": STEP_SCORE_PROMPT.format(\n            problem=problem,\n            prior_steps=\"\\n\".join(f\"{i+1}. {s}\" for i, s in enumerate(prior_steps)),\n            current_step=current_step,\n        )}],\n    ).content[0].text.strip()\n    try:\n        clean = re.sub(r\"^```[a-z]*\\n|```$\", \"\", raw, flags=re.M).strip()\n        return json.loads(clean)\n    except Exception:\n        return {\"score\": 0.5, \"reason\": \"parse error\"}\n\ndef score_chain(problem: str, steps: list[str]) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Score every step in a reasoning chain, returning step-level scores.\"\"\"\n    results = []\n    for i, step in enumerate(steps):\n        result = score_step(problem, steps[:i], step)\n        results.append({\"step\": i + 1, \"text\": step[:80], **result})\n    return results\n\n# Example\nproblem = \"If a train travels 120 miles in 2 hours, then speeds up by 20 mph for another hour, what is the total distance?\"\nsteps = [\n    \"Initial speed = 120 / 2 = 60 mph.\",\n    \"New speed = 60 + 20 = 80 mph.\",\n    \"Distance in third hour = 80 * 1 = 80 miles.\",\n    \"Total distance = 120 + 80 = 200 miles.\",\n]\nscores = score_chain(problem, steps)\nfor s in scores:\n    print(f\"Step {s['step']} ({s['score']:.2f}): {s['text'][:60]}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Aggregating Step Scores"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A PRM produces one score per step. To compare whole chains (for Best-of-N or filtering), these step scores must be aggregated into a single chain score. The choice of aggregation affects which error pattern is most penalised:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass PRMResult:\n    steps: list[str]\n    step_scores: list[float]\n    min_score: float\n    product_score: float\n    mean_score: float\n\ndef aggregate_step_scores(step_scores: list[float]) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Compute common PRM aggregation strategies.\"\"\"\n    import math\n    return {\n        \"min\":     min(step_scores),\n        \"product\": math.prod(step_scores),\n        \"mean\":    sum(step_scores) / len(step_scores),\n        \"last\":    step_scores[-1],  # final step only (approximates ORM)\n    }\n\ndef prm_score_chain(problem: str, steps: list[str]) -> PRMResult:\n    \"\"\"Score a chain and return structured PRM result.\"\"\"\n    raw_scores = score_chain(problem, steps)\n    step_scores = [s[\"score\"] for s in raw_scores]\n    agg = aggregate_step_scores(step_scores)\n    return PRMResult(\n        steps=steps,\n        step_scores=step_scores,\n        min_score=agg[\"min\"],\n        product_score=agg[\"product\"],\n        mean_score=agg[\"mean\"],\n    )\n\n# Which aggregation to use?\n# min:     most conservative; flags any single bad step\n#          best when one wrong step invalidates the whole chain\n# product: penalises multiple weak steps cumulatively\n#          good for multi-step math where errors compound\n# mean:    tolerant of isolated weak steps\n#          better for long explanations with optional elaboration\n# last:    approximates ORM; ignores intermediate reasoning quality"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PRM-Guided Best-of-N"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In Best-of-N, the PRM replaces a simple verifier: generate N solution chains in parallel, score each chain's steps, and return the chain with the best aggregated score. This is more discriminating than scoring only the final answer because it selects chains with sound reasoning, not just lucky endpoints:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def sample_chain(problem: str) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"Ask Claude to produce a step-by-step solution and parse the steps.\"\"\"\n    resp = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=1024,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": (\n            f\"Solve this step by step. Number each step.\\n\\nProblem: {problem}\"\n        )}],\n    ).content[0].text\n    import re\n    steps = [re.sub(r\"^\\d+\\.\\s*\", \"\", ln).strip()\n             for ln in resp.splitlines() if re.match(r\"^\\d+\\.\", ln.strip())]\n    return steps if steps else [resp]\n\ndef prm_best_of_n(\n    problem: str,\n    n: int = 4,\n    aggregation: str = \"min\",\n) -> tuple[list[str], float]:\n    \"\"\"Generate N solution chains and return the one with the best PRM score.\"\"\"\n    with ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=n) as pool:\n        chains = list(pool.map(lambda _: sample_chain(problem), range(n)))\n\n    scored = []\n    for chain in chains:\n        result = prm_score_chain(problem, chain)\n        agg_score = getattr(result, f\"{aggregation}_score\")\n        scored.append((chain, agg_score))\n\n    best_chain, best_score = max(scored, key=lambda x: x[1])\n    return best_chain, best_score\n\nchain, score = prm_best_of_n(\n    problem=\"A store sells apples for $1.50 each. With a 15% discount on orders over 10, how much do 12 apples cost?\",\n    n=4,\n    aggregation=\"min\",\n)\nprint(f\"Best chain (min-score {score:.2f}):\")\nfor i, step in enumerate(chain):\n    print(f\"  {i+1}. {step}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PRM-Guided Beam Search"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Beam search uses PRM scores to prune bad reasoning paths at each step, focusing compute on promising directions. At each expansion round, new step candidates are scored and only those above a threshold are carried forward:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def prm_guided_beam_search(\n    problem: str,\n    beam_width: int = 3,\n    max_steps: int = 6,\n    min_step_score: float = 0.5,\n) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Beam search over reasoning steps guided by PRM scores.\n    At each step, expand beam_width candidates and keep only\n    those scoring above min_step_score.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Each beam state is (prior_steps, last_step_score)\n    beams: list[tuple[list[str], float]] = [([], 1.0)]\n\n    NEXT_STEP_PROMPT = (\n        \"Problem: {problem}\\n\"\n        \"Steps so far:\\n{steps}\\n\"\n        \"Write the next single reasoning step. If the problem is solved, write DONE.\"\n    )\n\n    for _ in range(max_steps):\n        candidates = []\n        for prior_steps, _ in beams:\n            for _ in range(beam_width):\n                resp = client.messages.create(\n                    model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n                    max_tokens=256,\n                    temperature=0.7,\n                    messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": NEXT_STEP_PROMPT.format(\n                        problem=problem,\n                        steps=\"\\n\".join(f\"{i+1}. {s}\" for i, s in enumerate(prior_steps)),\n                    )}],\n                ).content[0].text.strip()\n                candidates.append((prior_steps, resp))\n\n        # Score each candidate step\n        scored = []\n        for prior_steps, new_step in candidates:\n            if \"DONE\" in new_step.upper():\n                return prior_steps  # Solution found\n            result = score_step(problem, prior_steps, new_step)\n            step_score = result[\"score\"]\n            if step_score >= min_step_score:\n                scored.append((prior_steps + [new_step], step_score))\n\n        if not scored:\n            break  # All candidates below threshold -- give up\n\n        # Keep top beam_width beams by step score\n        beams = sorted(scored, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:beam_width]\n\n    # Return the best beam found\n    return beams[0][0] if beams else []\n\nsolution = prm_guided_beam_search(\n    problem=\"Find x: 3(x - 2) + 7 = 4x - 1\",\n    beam_width=2,\n    max_steps=5,\n)\nprint(\"Solution steps:\", solution)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Finding and Fixing the First Bad Step"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A PRM can pinpoint exactly where a reasoning chain goes wrong. Once the first bad step is identified, the correct prefix can be preserved and regeneration begins from that point:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def extract_first_bad_step(\n    problem: str,\n    steps: list[str],\n    threshold: float = 0.5,\n) -> int | None:\n    \"\"\"Return the index of the first step scoring below threshold, or None.\"\"\"\n    for i, step in enumerate(steps):\n        result = score_step(problem, steps[:i], step)\n        if result[\"score\"] < threshold:\n            return i\n    return None\n\ndef prm_guided_revision(problem: str, steps: list[str]) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Find the first bad step, truncate the chain there,\n    and regenerate from that point.\n    \"\"\"\n    bad_idx = extract_first_bad_step(problem, steps)\n    if bad_idx is None:\n        return steps  # No bad step found\n\n    good_prefix = steps[:bad_idx]\n    fix_prompt = (\n        f\"Problem: {problem}\\n\"\n        f\"Correct steps so far:\\n\"\n        + \"\\n\".join(f\"{i+1}. {s}\" for i, s in enumerate(good_prefix))\n        + f\"\\n\\nStep {bad_idx + 1} was incorrect. Continue solving from step {bad_idx + 1}.\"\n    )\n    continuation = client.messages.create(\n        model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n        max_tokens=1024,\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": fix_prompt}],\n    ).content[0].text\n    import re\n    new_steps = [re.sub(r\"^\\d+\\.\\s*\", \"\", ln).strip()\n                 for ln in continuation.splitlines()\n                 if re.match(r\"^\\d+\\.\", ln.strip())]\n    return good_prefix + new_steps\n\n# Usage\nbad_chain = [\n    \"Speed = 120 / 2 = 50 mph.\",  # wrong: should be 60\n    \"New speed = 50 + 20 = 70 mph.\",\n    \"Total = 120 + 70 = 190 miles.\",\n]\nproblem = \"A train travels 120 miles in 2 hours, then speeds up by 20 mph for 1 hour. Total distance?\"\nrevised = prm_guided_revision(problem, bad_chain)\nprint(\"Revised chain:\", revised)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to Use PRMs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Multi-step arithmetic and algebra: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "The canonical PRM use case. Errors in early steps invalidate all subsequent steps; step-level detection finds them early."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Symbolic reasoning and proofs: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Logical deduction chains where one invalid inference breaks the whole argument. Min-aggregation flags any step that violates the logic."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Code generation with debugging: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Each line of code can be scored for correctness in context. A PRM can flag the line that introduces a bug before execution."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Agent planning: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Multi-step plans where an early action choice forecloses a valid solution. PRM scores on plan steps guide search toward feasible action sequences."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Skip for single-turn factual tasks: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If the problem has no intermediate steps (a direct lookup, a classification), the ORM is sufficient and cheaper."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Limitations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "N-times more expensive than ORM: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A 5-step chain requires 5 score calls vs 1. Parallelise where possible; consider scoring only on candidate filtering, not every generation."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Step granularity is task-dependent: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "What counts as a 'step' varies. For math, numbered steps work well. For prose reasoning, step boundaries are ambiguous and must be defined explicitly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "LLM-as-PRM can make the same errors as the generator: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If the scoring LLM shares parametric weaknesses with the generator (e.g. both make the same arithmetic mistake), the PRM will score bad steps as good."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Training data scarcity: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Trained PRMs require step-level human annotations, which are expensive to collect. LLM-simulated PRMs trade annotation cost for inference cost."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "PRMs score each reasoning step, "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "catching errors that ORMs miss because they only see the final answer."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Use min-aggregation "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "for strict correctness requirements (one bad step = chain rejected); use mean for tasks where isolated weak steps are acceptable."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Combine PRM with Best-of-N "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "to select the chain with the best reasoning quality across N samples, not just the one with the best-sounding final answer."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Beam search with step-level pruning "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "focuses compute on promising reasoning paths and terminates bad chains before they complete."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}